{"title_page": "Peter Beard", "text_new": "{{other people}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = Peter Beard\n| image              = PeterBeardGiraffes-HogRanch2014-wiki.jpg\n| caption            = Beard in 2014\n| birth_date         = {{Birth date|1938|01|22|mf=y}}\n| birth_place        = New York, United States\n| disappeared_place  = March 31, 2020<br>[[Montauk, New York]], U.S.\n| death_date         = [[Circa|c.]] March 31/April 2020<br>(aged 82)\n| death_place        = [[Montauk Point, New York]], U.S. \n| death_cause        = \n| body_discovered    = [[Camp Hero State Park]]<br>April 19, 2020\n|nationality         = American\n| education          = [[Pomfret School]]\n| alma_mater         = [[Yale University]]\n| occupation         = [[Artist]]\n| title              = \n| spouse             = {{marriage|Minnie Cushing Beard Coleman|1962|1963|end=divorced}}<br/>{{marriage|[[Cheryl Tiegs]]|1982|1986|end=divorced}}<br/>{{marriage|Nejma Khanum|1986|2020|end=his death}}\n| children           = 1\n| website            = {{URL|www.peterbeard.com}}\n}}\n\n'''Peter Hill Beard''' (January 22, 1938 &ndash; [[Circa|c.]] March/April 2020) was an American artist, [[photographer]], [[diarist]] and writer who lived and worked in New York City, Montauk, and Kenya.  His photographs of Africa, [[African animals]] and the journals that often integrated his photographs were widely shown and published since the 1960s.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://peterbeard.com/|title=Peter Beard Studio|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-16}}</ref>\n\n==Early life and education==\n\nPeter Beard was born in 1938 as a New York heir to a railroad fortune on his mother's side of the family and a tobacco inheritance on his father's.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://nymag.com/news/features/peter-beard-2013-3/index1.html|title=Taming Peter Beard|website=NYMag.com|access-date=2018-01-08}}</ref> He was raised in New York City, [[Alabama]], and [[Islip, New York|Islip]], [[Long Island]], Beard began keeping diaries as a young boy and making photographs, as an extension of the diaries, at the age of 12.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Beard|first1=Peter|title=Peter Beard|date=2013|publisher=Owen, & Aronson|location=Germany|isbn=978-3-8365-3088-0|edition=Collector's}}</ref> A graduate of [[Pomfret School]], he entered [[Yale University]] in 1957, with the intention of pursuing pre-med studies, only to switch his major to [[art history]]. At Yale, he was tapped into the secret society [[Scroll and Key]]. His mentors at Yale included [[Josef Albers]], [[Richard Lindner (painter)|Richard Lindner]] and [[Vincent Scully]].\n\nInspired by earlier trips to Africa in both 1955 and 1960, Beard traveled to [[Kenya]] upon graduation. Working at [[Tsavo Conservation Area|Tsavo National Park]], he photographed and documented the demise of 35,000 [[elephant]]s and other wildlife, later to become the subject of his first book, ''The End of the Game''.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Beard|first1=Peter|title=The End of the Game|date=1965|publisher=Viking Press|location=New York|isbn=978-3-8365-0530-7}}</ref>  During this time, Beard acquired Hog Ranch, a property near the [[Ngong Hills]] adjacent to the coffee farm owned by [[Karen Blixen]] (Isak Dinesen), which would become his lifelong home-base in [[East Africa]].<ref>{{cite book|last1=Beard|first1=Peter|title=Peter Beard|date=2013|publisher=Owen, & Aronson|location=Germany|isbn=978-3-8365-3088-0|edition=Collector's}}</ref>\n\n==Art==\n\nBeard's photographs of Africa, African animals and journals that often integrate his photographs have been widely shown and published since the 1970s. Each of his works is unique, a combination of his photography with elements derived from his daily diary-keeping, a practice he continued until his death in 2020. These volumes contain newspaper clippings, dried leaves, insects, old [[sepia tone|sepia]]-toned photos, transcribed telephone messages, [[marginalia]] in [[India ink]], photographs of women, quotes, found objects, and the like; these become incorporated, with original drawings and collage by Beard. Certain of his works incorporate animal blood, sometimes Beard's own blood (in sparing quantities), a painting medium the artist favored.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Enright|first1=Robert|title=The Consummate Fragmentarian|journal=Modern Painters Magazine|date=2002}}</ref>\n\nThe Peter Beard Studio and Archive was started by Peter and Nejma Beard, and is the primary source for artwork by Peter Beard.\u00a0 The Archive maintains a repository of published and unpublished written and visual material relating to the artist\u2019s life, work, projects, travels, exhibitions, and relations with his cohort.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://peterbeard.com/|title=Peter Beard Studio|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-16}}</ref>\n\nBeard's first exhibition was at the Blum Helman Gallery, New York City, in 1975.  Landmark museum exhibitions have been held at the [[International Center of Photography]], New York City, in 1977, and the [[Centre national de la photographie]], Paris, in 1997. Gallery exhibitions followed in Berlin, London, Toronto, Madrid, Milan, Tokyo and Vienna. Beard's work is included in private collections throughout the world.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Beard|first1=Peter|title=Peter Beard|date=2013|publisher=Owen, & Aronson|location=Germany|isbn=978-3-8365-3088-0|edition=Collector's}}</ref>\n\nIn 2017, Beard was sued by actor [[David Spade]] who purchased one of his works. Spade tried to resell a Peter Beard photograph that he had purchased from dealer [[Peter Tunney]] but the unsigned work could not be authenticated.<ref name=artnet>{{cite news |last=Kinsella|first= Eileen|date=February 3, 2017 |title=Actor David Spade Sues Photographer Peter Beard for Failure to Authenticate a Work |url=https://news.artnet.com/art-world/david-spade-sues-photographer-peter-beard-844637 |newspaper=Artnet.com|access-date=February 3, 2017 }}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\n\nDescended from distinguished American families on both sides, Beard was one of three sons born to Roseanne Hoar Beard and Anson McCook Beard, Jr.  A great-grandfather, [[James Jerome Hill]], was founder of the [[Great Northern Railway (U.S.)|Great Northern Railway]] in the [[United States]] in the late 19th/early 20th centuries. Having made his fortune in the railroad business, James Jerome Hill was a great patron of the arts.  All of his heirs were exposed to and owned great collections, presumably having a strong influence on Beard\u2019s interests in the arts and beauty.\n\nBeard married his first wife (Minnie Cushing Beard Coleman) in 1967; their marriage lasted only briefly. His second wife was [[supermodel]] [[Cheryl Tiegs]], from 1982 to 1986.\n\nIn 1986, he married Nejma Khanum. The couple has a daughter, Zara, for whom his book, Zara\u2019s Tales,<ref>{{cite book|last1=Beard|first1=Peter|title=Zara's Tales: Perilous Escapades in Equatorial Africa|date=2004|publisher=Knopf|location=New York|isbn=0-679-42659-0|url=https://archive.org/details/zarastalesfromho00bear}}</ref> was written.\n\nIn 1996 he waa charged by an elephant and gored in the right leg. After arriving at the hospital without a pulse, he was revived, and survived.<ref>https://www.nytimes.com/2020/04/19/arts/peter-beard-dead.html?smid=fb-share</ref><ref> Alec Baldwin with Peter Beard: The Elephant Attack [https://www.americansuburbx.com/2016/01/alec-baldwin-with-peter-beard-the-elephant-attack.html www.americansuburbx.com]</ref>\n\nBeard befriended and in some cases collaborated with many legendary artists including [[Andy Warhol]], [[Andrew Wyeth]], [[Francis Bacon (artist)|Francis Bacon]], [[Karen Blixen]], [[Truman Capote]], [[Richard Lindner (painter)|Richard Lindner]], and [[Salvador Dal\u00ed]]. He also photographed many well-known people.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Beard|first1=Peter|title=Peter Beard|date=2013|publisher=Owen, & Aronson|location=Germany|isbn=978-3-8365-3088-0|edition=Collector's}}</ref>\n\n==Disappearance and death==\nOn March 31, 2020, Beard wandered away from his [[Montauk, Long Island]], home off Old Montauk Highway east of Deep Hollow Ranch around 4:40 pm. At the time of his disappearance, he was suffering from [[dementia]] and ill health after a [[stroke]]. Despite exhaustive searches, he was not found.<ref> Peter Beard Missing, Search Underway in Montauk [https://www.easthamptonstar.com/police-courts/202041/peter-beard-missing-search-underway-montauk]</ref> After three days, the case was turned over to detectives in the East Hampton Police Department. \n\nOn April 19, 2020, Beard\u2019s body was found by a hunter David Schleifer (retired NYC Firefighter) in a densely wooded area in [[Camp Hero State Park]] in [[Montauk Point, New York]].<ref>{{cite web |last1=Stowe |first1=Stacey |title=Peter Beard\u2019s Family Confirms His Death |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/04/19/arts/design/peter-beard-found-montauk.amp.html |website=The New York Times |publisher=nytimes.com |accessdate=April 19, 2020 |date=April 19, 2020}}</ref> A cause of death has yet to be determined.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Fox |first1=Margalit |title=Peter Beard, Wildlife Photographer on the Wild Side, Dies at 82 |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/04/19/arts/peter-beard-dead.amp.html |website=The New York Times |publisher=nytimes.com |accessdate=April 20, 2020 |date=April 20, 2020}}</ref> He was 82.\n\n==Filmography==\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Year !! Film !! Featured !! Director !! Producer !! Editor !! Other\n|-\n| 2017 || ''That Summer'' || Yes || No || Yes || No || No \n|-\n| 2009 || ''The Making of the 2009 Pirelli Calendar'' || Yes || No || No || No || No \n|-\n| 1994 || ''Montauk Diaries'' || Yes || No || No || No || No \n|-\n| 1988 || ''Last Word from Paradise: With Peter Beard in Africa'' || Yes || No || No || No || No \n|-\n| 1980 || ''Japanese Long Line Tuna Fishing'' || No || No || No || No || Introducer \n|-\n| 1979 || ''Africa: The End of the Game'' || Yes || No || No || No || No \n|-\n| 1976 || ''The Bicentennial Big Foot Blues'' || No || Yes || Yes || No || No \n|-\n| 1975-76 || ''Longing for Darkness'' || No || No || Yes || Yes || No \n|-\n| 1972 || ''Sisters'' (working title) || Yes || Yes || Yes || No || Initiated\n|-\n| 1963 || ''[[Hallelujah the Hills (film)|Hallelujah the Hills]]'' || Yes || No || No || No || No \n|}\n\n==Publications==\n===Selected books===\n\n* Graham, Alistair, and Beard, Peter (1973). Eyelids of Morning: The Mingled Destinies of Crocodiles and Men. Greenwich, CT: New York Graphic Society. {{ISBN|0-8212-0464-5}}\n* Beard, Peter; and Gatura, Kamante (1975). Longing for Darkness: Kamante's Tales from Out of Africa. New York: Harcourt Brace Jovanovich. {{ISBN|0-15-153080-7}}\n* Beard, Peter (2004). Zara's Tales: Perilous Escapades in Equatorial Africa. New York: Knopf. {{ISBN|0-679-42659-0}}\n* Beard, Peter (1965). The End of the Game. New York: Viking Press.  Reprinted New York: Doubleday, 1977.  Japan: Camera Manichi, 1978.  Germany: Taschen, 2008.  {{ISBN|978-3-8365-0530-7}}\n* Beard, Peter; Beard, Nejma; Edwards, Owen; Aronson, Steven M.L. (2008). Peter Beard (Collector\u2019s Edition). Germany: Taschen, 2006. (Art Edition) Germany: Taschen, 2007.  (Trade Edition) Germany: Taschen, 2008, 2013, and 2020. {{ISBN|978-3-8365-7742-7}}\n* Beard, Peter; Paul Theroux.  50th Anniversary Edition of The End of the Game.  Taschen.  [https://www.taschen.org ISBN]-978-3-8365-5547-0\n\n===Catalogues===\n\n* Beard, Peter (1993). Diary: From a Dead Man\u2019s Wallet: Confessions of a Bookmaker. Japan: Libroport Publishing Co., Ltd. {{ISBN|978-4-8457-0791-1}}\n* Beard, Peter, and Caujolle, Christian (1996). Peter Beard: Photo Poche #67. Paris: Centre national de la photographie, {{ISBN|2867541034}}\n* Beard, Peter (1997). Oltre la fine del Mondo. Milan: Grafiche Milani.\n* Beard, Peter (1998). Beyond the End of the World. Milan: Universe Publishing (a division of Rizzoli International Publications, Inc.).  {{ISBN|978-0-7893-0147-5}}\n* Beard, Peter (1999). Peter Beard: Stress & Density. Vienna: KunstHausWien, Museums Betriebs Gesellschaft, mbH. {{ISBN|978-3901247071}}\n* Beard, Peter (1999). Peter Beard: Fifty Years of Portraits. Santa Fe, NM: Arena Editions. {{ISBN|1-892041-15-4}}\n\n==Further reading==\n\n* Geldzahler, Henry (1975).  Francis Bacon: Recent Paintings.  Interview with Francis Bacon by Peter Beard.  New York: [[The Metropolitan Museum of Art]].\n* Bowermaster, Jon (1993). The adventures and misadventures of Peter Beard in Africa. Boston: [[Bulfinch Press]], 1993. {{ISBN|0-8212-1907-3}}\n\n==References==\n\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Wikiquote}}\n* {{official website|www.peterbeard.com}}\n\n{{Use mdy dates|date=April 2014}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Beard, Peter}}\n[[Category:1938 births]]\n[[Category:2020 deaths]]\n[[Category:20th-century American photographers]]\n[[Category:20th-century American writers]]\n[[Category:American diarists]]\n[[Category:American photographers]]\n[[Category:American portrait photographers]]\n[[Category:American socialites]] \n[[Category:Artists from New York (state)]]\n[[Category:Nature photographers]]\n[[Category:Pomfret School alumni]]\n[[Category:Writers from New York (state)]]\n[[Category:Yale University alumni]]\n[[Category:Formerly missing people found dead]]\n", "text_old": "{{other people}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = Peter Beard\n| image              = PeterBeardGiraffes-HogRanch2014-wiki.jpg\n| caption            = Beard in 2014\n| birth_date         = {{Birth date|1938|01|22|mf=y}}\n| birth_place        = New York, United States\n| disappeared_place  = March 31, 2020<br>[[Montauk, New York]], U.S.\n| death_date         = [[Circa|c.]] March 31/April 2020<br>(aged 82)\n| death_place        = [[Montauk Point, New York]], U.S. \n| death_cause        = \n| body_discovered    = [[Camp Hero State Park]]<br>April 19, 2020\n|nationality         = American\n| education          = [[Pomfret School]]\n| alma_mater         = [[Yale University]]\n| occupation         = [[Artist]]\n| title              = \n| spouse             = {{marriage|Minnie Cushing Beard Coleman|1962|1963|end=divorced}}<br/>{{marriage|[[Cheryl Tiegs]]|1982|1986|end=divorced}}<br/>{{marriage|Nejma Khanum|1986|2020|end=his death}}\n| children           = 1\n| website            = http://www.peterbeard.com/\n}}\n\n'''Peter Hill Beard''' (January 22, 1938 &ndash; [[Circa|c.]] March/April 2020) was an American artist, [[photographer]], [[diarist]] and writer who lived and worked in [[New York City]], [[Montauk, New York|Montauk]], and [[Kenya]].  His photographs of [[Africa]], [[African animals]] and the journals that often integrated his photographs were widely shown and published since the 1960s.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://peterbeard.com/|title=Peter Beard Studio|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-16}}</ref>\n\n==Early life and education==\n\nPeter Beard was born in 1938 as a New York heir to a railroad fortune on his mother's side of the family and a tobacco inheritance on his father's.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://nymag.com/news/features/peter-beard-2013-3/index1.html|title=Taming Peter Beard|website=NYMag.com|access-date=2018-01-08}}</ref> He was raised in New York City, [[Alabama]], and [[Islip, New York|Islip]], [[Long Island]], Beard began keeping diaries as a young boy and making photographs, as an extension of the diaries, at the age of 12.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Beard|first1=Peter|title=Peter Beard|date=2013|publisher=Owen, & Aronson|location=Germany|isbn=978-3-8365-3088-0|edition=Collector's}}</ref> A graduate of [[Pomfret School]], he entered [[Yale University]] in 1957, with the intention of pursuing pre-med studies, only to switch his major to [[art history]]. At Yale, he was tapped into the secret society [[Scroll and Key]]. His mentors at Yale included [[Josef Albers]], [[Richard Lindner (painter)|Richard Lindner]] and [[Vincent Scully]].\n\nInspired by earlier trips to Africa in both 1955 and 1960, Beard traveled to [[Kenya]] upon graduation. Working at [[Tsavo Conservation Area|Tsavo National Park]], he photographed and documented the demise of 35,000 [[elephant]]s and other wildlife, later to become the subject of his first book, ''The End of the Game''.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Beard|first1=Peter|title=The End of the Game|date=1965|publisher=Viking Press|location=New York|isbn=978-3-8365-0530-7}}</ref>  During this time, Beard acquired Hog Ranch, a property near the [[Ngong Hills]] adjacent to the coffee farm owned by [[Karen Blixen]] (Isak Dinesen), which would become his lifelong home-base in [[East Africa]].<ref>{{cite book|last1=Beard|first1=Peter|title=Peter Beard|date=2013|publisher=Owen, & Aronson|location=Germany|isbn=978-3-8365-3088-0|edition=Collector's}}</ref>\n\n==Art==\n\nBeard's photographs of Africa, African animals and journals that often integrate his photographs have been widely shown and published since the 1970s. Each of his works is unique, a combination of his photography with elements derived from his daily diary-keeping, a practice he continued until his death in 2020. These volumes contain newspaper clippings, dried leaves, insects, old [[sepia tone|sepia]]-toned photos, transcribed telephone messages, [[marginalia]] in [[India ink]], photographs of women, quotes, found objects, and the like; these become incorporated, with original drawings and collage by Beard. Certain of his works incorporate animal blood, sometimes Beard's own blood (in sparing quantities), a painting medium the artist favored.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Enright|first1=Robert|title=The Consummate Fragmentarian|journal=Modern Painters Magazine|date=2002}}</ref>\n\nThe Peter Beard Studio and Archive was started by Peter and Nejma Beard, and is the primary source for artwork by Peter Beard.\u00a0 The Archive maintains a repository of published and unpublished written and visual material relating to the artist\u2019s life, work, projects, travels, exhibitions, and relations with his cohort.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://peterbeard.com/|title=Peter Beard Studio|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-16}}</ref>\n\nBeard's first exhibition was at the Blum Helman Gallery, New York City, in 1975.  Landmark museum exhibitions have been held at the [[International Center of Photography]], New York City, in 1977, and the [[Centre national de la photographie]], Paris, in 1997. Gallery exhibitions followed in Berlin, London, Toronto, Madrid, Milan, Tokyo and Vienna. Beard's work is included in private collections throughout the world.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Beard|first1=Peter|title=Peter Beard|date=2013|publisher=Owen, & Aronson|location=Germany|isbn=978-3-8365-3088-0|edition=Collector's}}</ref>\n\nIn 2017, Beard was sued by actor [[David Spade]] who purchased one of his works. Spade tried to resell a Peter Beard photograph that he had purchased from dealer [[Peter Tunney]] but the unsigned work could not be authenticated.<ref name=artnet>{{cite news |last=Kinsella|first= Eileen|date=February 3, 2017 |title=Actor David Spade Sues Photographer Peter Beard for Failure to Authenticate a Work |url=https://news.artnet.com/art-world/david-spade-sues-photographer-peter-beard-844637 |newspaper=Artnet.com|access-date=February 3, 2017 }}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\n\nDescended from distinguished American families on both sides, Beard was one of three sons born to Roseanne Hoar Beard and Anson McCook Beard, Jr.  A great-grandfather, [[James Jerome Hill]], was founder of the [[Great Northern Railway (U.S.)|Great Northern Railway]] in the [[United States]] in the late 19th/early 20th centuries. Having made his fortune in the railroad business, James Jerome Hill was a great patron of the arts.  All of his heirs were exposed to and owned great collections, presumably having a strong influence on Beard\u2019s interests in the arts and beauty.\n\nBeard married his first wife (Minnie Cushing Beard Coleman) in 1967; their marriage lasted only briefly. His second wife was [[supermodel]] [[Cheryl Tiegs]], from 1982 to 1986.\n\nIn 1986, he married Nejma Khanum. The couple has a daughter, Zara, for whom his book, Zara\u2019s Tales,<ref>{{cite book|last1=Beard|first1=Peter|title=Zara's Tales: Perilous Escapades in Equatorial Africa|date=2004|publisher=Knopf|location=New York|isbn=0-679-42659-0|url=https://archive.org/details/zarastalesfromho00bear}}</ref> was written.\n\nIn 1996 he waa charged by an elephant and gored in the right leg. After arriving at the hospital without a pulse, he was revived, and survived.<ref>https://www.nytimes.com/2020/04/19/arts/peter-beard-dead.html?smid=fb-share</ref><ref> Alec Baldwin with Peter Beard: The Elephant Attack [https://www.americansuburbx.com/2016/01/alec-baldwin-with-peter-beard-the-elephant-attack.html www.americansuburbx.com]</ref>\n\nBeard befriended and in some cases collaborated with many legendary artists including [[Andy Warhol]], [[Andrew Wyeth]], [[Francis Bacon (artist)|Francis Bacon]], [[Karen Blixen]], [[Truman Capote]], [[Richard Lindner (painter)|Richard Lindner]], and [[Salvador Dal\u00ed]]. He also photographed many well-known people.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Beard|first1=Peter|title=Peter Beard|date=2013|publisher=Owen, & Aronson|location=Germany|isbn=978-3-8365-3088-0|edition=Collector's}}</ref>\n\n==Disappearance and death==\nOn March 31, 2020, Beard wandered away from his [[Montauk, Long Island]], home off Old Montauk Highway east of Deep Hollow Ranch around 4:40 pm. At the time of his disappearance, he was suffering from [[dementia]] and ill health after a [[stroke]]. Despite exhaustive searches, he was not found.<ref> Peter Beard Missing, Search Underway in Montauk [https://www.easthamptonstar.com/police-courts/202041/peter-beard-missing-search-underway-montauk]</ref> After three days, the case was turned over to detectives in the East Hampton Police Department. \n\nOn April 19, 2020, Beard\u2019s body was found by a hunter David Schleifer (retired NYC Firefighter) in a densely wooded area in [[Camp Hero State Park]] in [[Montauk Point, New York]].<ref>{{cite web |last1=Stowe |first1=Stacey |title=Peter Beard\u2019s Family Confirms His Death |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/04/19/arts/design/peter-beard-found-montauk.amp.html |website=The New York Times |publisher=nytimes.com |accessdate=April 19, 2020 |date=April 19, 2020}}</ref> A cause of death has yet to be determined.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Fox |first1=Margalit |title=Peter Beard, Wildlife Photographer on the Wild Side, Dies at 82 |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/04/19/arts/peter-beard-dead.amp.html |website=The New York Times |publisher=nytimes.com |accessdate=April 20, 2020 |date=April 20, 2020}}</ref> He was 82.\n\n==Filmography==\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Year !! Film !! Featured !! Director !! Producer !! Editor !! Other\n|-\n| 2017 || ''That Summer'' || Yes || No || Yes || No || No \n|-\n| 2009 || ''The Making of the 2009 Pirelli Calendar'' || Yes || No || No || No || No \n|-\n| 1994 || ''Montauk Diaries'' || Yes || No || No || No || No \n|-\n| 1988 || ''Last Word from Paradise: With Peter Beard in Africa'' || Yes || No || No || No || No \n|-\n| 1980 || ''Japanese Long Line Tuna Fishing'' || No || No || No || No || Introducer \n|-\n| 1979 || ''Africa: The End of the Game'' || Yes || No || No || No || No \n|-\n| 1976 || ''The Bicentennial Big Foot Blues'' || No || Yes || Yes || No || No \n|-\n| 1975-76 || ''Longing for Darkness'' || No || No || Yes || Yes || No \n|-\n| 1972 || ''Sisters'' (working title) || Yes || Yes || Yes || No || Initiated\n|-\n| 1963 || ''[[Hallelujah the Hills (film)|Hallelujah the Hills]]'' || Yes || No || No || No || No \n|}\n\n==Selected books==\n\n* Graham, Alistair, and Beard, Peter (1973). Eyelids of Morning: The Mingled Destinies of Crocodiles and Men. Greenwich, CT: New York Graphic Society. {{ISBN|0-8212-0464-5}}\n* Beard, Peter; and Gatura, Kamante (1975). Longing for Darkness: Kamante's Tales from Out of Africa. 