{"title_page": "Midway (2019 film)", "text_new": "{{short description|2019 film directed by Roland Emmerich}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = Midway\n| image          = Midway Movie HD Poster.jpeg\n| alt            = \n| caption        = Theatrical release poster\n| director       = [[Roland Emmerich]]\n| producer       = {{Plainlist|\n* Roland Emmerich\n* [[Harald Kloser]]\n}}\n| writer         = Wes Tooke\n| based on       = \n| starring       = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Ed Skrein]]\n* [[Patrick Wilson (American actor)|Patrick Wilson]]\n* [[Luke Evans]]\n* [[Aaron Eckhart]]\n* [[Nick Jonas]]\n* [[Etsushi Toyokawa]]\n* [[Tadanobu Asano]]\n* [[Luke Kleintank]]\n* [[Jun Kunimura]]\n* [[Darren Criss]]\n* [[Keean Johnson]]\n* [[Mandy Moore]]\n* [[Dennis Quaid]]\n* [[Woody Harrelson]]\n}}\n| music          = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Thomas Wander]]\n* Harald Kloser\n}}\n| cinematography = Robby Baumgartner\n| editing        = {{Plainlist|\n* Adam Wolfe\n}}\n| studio       = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Summit Entertainment]]\n* [[Centropolis Entertainment]]\n* [[Entertainment One]]\n* RuYi Media\n* Starlight Culture Entertainment Group\n* Street Entertainment\n* AGC Studios\n}}\n| distributor    = [[Lionsgate]]\n| released       = {{Film date|2019|11|8|United States}}\n| runtime        = 138 minutes\n| country        = United States\n| language       = English\n| budget         = $100 million<ref name=Budget>{{cite news|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/box-office-doctor-sleep-midway-surprise-battle-no-1-1253534|title=Box Office: 'Midway' Downs 'Doctor Sleep' in Surprise Upset |date=November 8, 2019|work=The Hollywood Reporter |author1=Pamela McClintock}}</ref>\n| gross          = $125.8 million<ref name=\"BOM\">{{Cite web |url= https://www.boxofficemojo.com/title/tt6924650 |title=Midway (2019) |website=[[Box Office Mojo]] |accessdate=January 17, 2020}}</ref>\n}}\n\n'''''Midway''''' is a 2019 American  [[Epic film|epic]] [[war film]] directed by [[Roland Emmerich]], who produced the film with [[Harald Kloser]], and written by Wes Tooke. The film features an [[ensemble cast]], including [[Ed Skrein]], [[Patrick Wilson (American actor)|Patrick Wilson]], [[Luke Evans]], [[Aaron Eckhart]], [[Nick Jonas]], [[Mandy Moore]], [[Dennis Quaid]], [[Tadanobu Asano]], and [[Woody Harrelson]].\n\nA passion project of Emmerich's, he had trouble getting financial support for the film before finally fundraising most of the budget and officially announcing it in 2017. Much of the cast joined in summer 2018, and filming began in [[Hawaii]] that September, also taking place in [[Montreal]]. With a production budget of $100 million, it is one of the most expensive [[independent films]] of all time.\n\n''Midway'' was theatrically released by [[Lionsgate]] in the United States on November 8, 2019. It received mixed reviews from critics and grossed $125 million worldwide.\n\n== Plot ==\nThe film follows the story of US Navy sailors and aviators who persevere through the [[Battle of Midway]], a turning point in the [[Pacific Ocean theater of World War II|Pacific Theater]] of [[World War II]]. It follows two threads: one centered on naval aviator Ensign [[Richard Halsey Best|Dick Best]] and the Air Group (CAG) of the carrier [[USS Enterprise (CV-6)|''Enterprise'']], and the other on intelligence officer [[Edwin T. Layton]].\n\nThe film starts with the US Naval attach\u00e9 in [[Tokyo]] and his counterpart discussing the US and Japanese positions in the Pacific Ocean during a state function in December 1937. Admiral [[Isoroku Yamamoto]] warns Layton that if the Japanese oil supply is threatened by the US, the Japanese will take immediate action. The story then goes on briefly to show the [[Attack on Pearl Harbor]] (December 1941), the [[Marshalls-Gilberts raids]] (February 1942), [[Doolittle Raid]] (April 1942), and the [[Battle of the Coral Sea]] (May 1942). It finally describes the planning for the Battle of Midway (June 1942), depicting the creation of a complicated battle plan. [[Joseph Rochefort]] and his cryptology team begin intercepting messages concerning a location the Japanese identify as \"AF\". Layton speaks with Admiral [[Chester Nimitz]], who informs him that Washington believes \"AF\" to be a target in the South Pacific. Layton disagrees, believing the intended target to be [[Midway Atoll]]. \n\nAfter meeting with Rochefort, Nimitz instructs the team to find a way to definitively prove that \"AF\u201d is Midway. After Layton instructs Midway to telegraph in the clear (unencrypted) that they are suffering a water shortage, cryptologists working for Rochefort intercept Japanese communications concerning water shortages on \u201cAF\u201d, confirming that \"AF\" is indeed Midway. In preparation for an ambush of the Japanese fleet, Nimitz orders carriers [[USS Hornet (CV-8)|''Hornet'']] and ''Enterprise'' recalled from the Coral Sea and demands that the damaged [[USS Yorktown (CV-5)|'' Yorktown'']] be made ready for combat operations. \n\nDuring the first stages of the battle, the submarine USS Nautilus manages to slip through the defensive row of Japanese destroyers and fire a torpedo at a carrier. The torpedo misses, and Admiral [[Tamon Yamaguchi]] orders the IJN Arashi to sink the Nautilus while the Japanese carriers make a quick getaway. While Arashi is headed back to the fleet, the US carrier dive bombers led by [[C. Wade McClusky]] follow the destroyer's wake. The gamble pays off and three of the Japanese carriers are destroyed in the first attack during the Battle of Midway. \n\nSpruance then orders what is remaining of the US Air Group to finish off the last carrier. Along their route, they are intercepted by Japanese fighters and bombers on their way to destroy American carriers. A huge [[dogfight]] ensues and many planes from both sides are destroyed. The remaining American planes attack the Hiryu with Lieutenant Best scoring a critical hit with a 500-pound bomb; Hiryu is later scuttled by torpedoes from a Japanese destroyer. Half of the U.S. planes are destroyed in the battle, including most of the [[torpedo bomber]] squadrons.\n\nIn Pearl Harbor, Rochefort intercepts the Japanese order to withdraw and passes it to Layton, who then informs Nimitz and his elated staff. The movie ends with a scene revealing the fates of the principal characters.\n\n==Cast==\n\n=== Allies ===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|- \"\n!Actor\n!Role\n!Notes\n|-\n|[[Ed Skrein]]\n|[[Lieutenant (navy)|Lieutenant]] [[Richard Halsey Best|Richard \"Dick\" Best]]||[[Executive officer]], Bombing Squadron Six, {{USS|Enterprise|CV-6|6}}\n|-\n|[[Patrick Wilson (American actor)|Patrick Wilson]]\n|[[Lieutenant Commander (United States)|Lieutenant Commander]] [[Edwin T. Layton]]||Intelligence officer, [[United States Pacific Fleet|US Pacific Fleet]]\n|-\n|[[Luke Evans]]\n|[[Lieutenant Commander (United States)|Lieutenant Commander]] [[C. Wade McClusky|Wade McClusky]]\n|Air group commander, {{USS|Enterprise|CV-6|6}}\n|-\n|[[Aaron Eckhart]]\n|[[Lieutenant colonel (United States)|Lieutenant Colonel]] [[Jimmy Doolittle]]\n|[[United States Army Air Forces|USAAF]] flight commander, {{USS|Hornet|CV-8|6}}\n|-\n|[[Nick Jonas]]\n|[[Aviation machinist's mate|Aviation Machinist's Mate]] Bruno Gaido\n|Aviation crew, {{USS|Enterprise|CV-6|6}}\n|-\n|[[Woody Harrelson]]\n|[[Admiral (United States)|Admiral]] [[Chester W. Nimitz]]\n|[[Commander-in-chief]], [[United States Pacific Fleet|US Pacific Fleet]]\n|-\n|[[Dennis Quaid]]\n|[[Vice Admiral (United States)|Vice Admiral]] [[William Halsey Jr.|William \"Bull\" Halsey]]\n|Commander, [[Carrier_Strike_Group_2#Historical_background|Carrier Division Two]]\n|-\n|[[Darren Criss]]\n|[[Lieutenant Commander (United States)|Lieutenant Commander]] [[Eugene E. Lindsey|Eugene Lindsey]]\n|Commander, Torpedo Squadron 6, {{USS|Enterprise|CV-6|6}}\n|-\n|[[Jake Weber]]\n|[[Rear Admiral (United States)|Rear Admiral]] [[Raymond Spruance]]\n|Commander, [[Task Force 16]]\n|-\n|[[Brennan Brown]]\n|[[Commander (United States)|Commander]] [[Joseph Rochefort]]\n|[[Cryptanalysis|Chief Cryptanalyst]], [[Station HYPO|Fleet Radio Unit Pacific]]\n|-\n|[[Alexander Ludwig]]\n|[[Lieutenant (navy)|Lieutenant]] Roy Pearce\n|Watch officer, {{USS|Arizona|BB-39|6}}\n|-\n|[[David Hewlett]]\n|[[Admiral (United States)|Admiral]] [[Husband E. Kimmel]]\n|[[Commander-in-chief]], [[United States Pacific Fleet|US Pacific Fleet]]\n|-\n|[[Keean Johnson]]\n|[[Radioman|Chief Aviation Radioman]] James Murray\n|Radio operator, Bombing Squadron Six, {{USS|Enterprise|CV-6|6}}\n|-\n|[[Mark Rolston]]\n|[[Admiral (United States)|Admiral]] [[Ernest King]]\n|[[Chief of Naval Operations]]\n|-\n|[[Luke Kleintank]]\n|[[Lieutenant (navy)|Lieutenant]] Clarence Earle Dickinson\n|Pilot, Scouting Squadron 6, {{USS|Enterprise|CV-6|6}}\n|-\n|[[Brandon Sklenar]]\n|[[Ensign (rank)#United States|Ensign]] [[George H. Gay Jr.|George Gay]]\n|Pilot, [[VT-8|Torpedo Squadron 8]], {{USS|Hornet|CV-8|6}}\n|-\n|[[Jake Manley]]\n|[[Ensign (rank)#United States|Ensign]] Willie West<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.abookof.us/nextchapters/jake-manley|title=Jake Manley: Interview|last=|first=|date=May 18, 2019|work=A Book of Magazine|accessdate=June 3, 2019}}</ref>\n|Pilot, Bombing Squadron 6, {{USS|Enterprise|CV-6|6}}\n|-\n|Eric Davis\n|[[Captain (United States O-6)|Captain]] [[Miles Browning]]\n|Halsey's chief of staff, {{USS|Enterprise|CV-6|6}}\n|-\n|Kenny Leu\n|Zhu Xuesan\n|Chinese school teacher, who visited the US in 1992\n|-\n|[[James Carpinello]]\n|[[Lieutenant Commander (United States)|Lieutenant Commander]] [[William H. Brockman Jr.|William Brockman]]\n|[[Captain]], {{USS|Nautilus|SS-168|6}}\n|-\n|Russell Dennis Lewis\n|[[Ensign (rank)#United States|Ensign]] Frank Woodrow O'Flaherty\n|Pilot, Scouting Squadron 6, {{USS|Enterprise|CV-6|6}}\n|-\n|Jacob Blair\n|[[2nd lieutenant|2nd Lieutenant]] Hank Potter\n|[[United States Army Air Forces|USAAF]] flight navigator, {{USS|Hornet|CV-8|6}}\n|-\n|James Hicks\n|[[Lieutenant (junior grade)|Lieutenant Junior Grade]] Edwin Kroeger\n|Pilot, Bombing Squadron Six, {{USS|Enterprise|CV-6|6}}\n|-\n|[[Geoffrey Blake (actor)|Geoffrey Blake]]\n|Commander [[John Ford]]\n|[[Film director]] stationed at [[Midway Atoll|Midway Island]] on Special Duty\n|}\n\n=== Japanese ===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|- \"\n! style=\"width:125px;\" |Actor\n! style=\"width:200px;\" |Role\n! style=\"width:500px;\" |Notes\n|-\n|[[Tadanobu Asano]]\n|[[Rear Admiral]] [[Tamon Yamaguchi]]\n|Commander, [[Second Carrier Division|2nd Carrier Division]]\n|-\n|[[Etsushi Toyokawa]]\n|[[Admiral#Japan|Admiral]] [[Isoroku Yamamoto]]\n|[[Commander-in-chief]], [[Combined Fleet]]\n|-\n|[[Jun Kunimura]]\n|[[Vice Admiral]] [[Ch\u016bichi Nagumo]]\n|Commander, [[1st Air Fleet]] (''[[Kido Butai]]'')\n|-\n|[[Peter Shinkoda]]\n|[[Captain]] [[Minoru Genda]]\n|Air Operations Officer, [[1st Air Fleet]]\n|-\n|Nobuya Shimamoto\n|[[Captain]] Tomeo Kaku\n|Commanding Officer, [[Japanese aircraft carrier Hiry\u016b|''Hiry\u016b'']]\n|-\n|[[Hiro Kanagawa]]\n|[[Commander]] Isamu Fujita\n|Commanding Officer, [[Japanese destroyer Makigumo (1941)|''Makigumo'']]\n|-\n|Ken Takikawa\n|[[Lieutenant]] Takashi Moroishi\n|Torpedo Officer (XO), [[Japanese destroyer Makigumo (1941)|''Makigumo'']]\n|-\n|Hiromoto Ida\n|[[Army general|General]] [[Hideki Tojo]]\n|[[Prime Minister of Japan]]\n|-\n|Hiroaki Shintani\n|[[Emperor Hirohito]]\n|[[Emperor of Japan]]\n|-\n|Ryuta Kato\n|Japanese Junior Officer (Yamat)\n|Junior Officer, [[Japanese aircraft carrier Hiry\u016b|''Hiry\u016b'']]\n|}\n\n=== Civilians ===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|- \"\n! style=\"width:125px;\" |Actor\n! style=\"width:200px;\" |Role\n! style=\"width:500px;\" |Notes\n|-\n|[[Mandy Moore]]\n|Anne Best\n|Dick Best's wife\n|-\n|Rachael Perrell Fosket\n|Dagne Layton\n|Edwin Layton's wife\n|-\n|Dean Schaller\n|[[Jack MacKenzie]]\n|Ford's [[cameraman]]\n|-\n|Christie Brooke\n|Millicent McClusky\n|Wade McClusky's wife\n|}\n\n== Production ==\nOn May 23, 2017, it was reported that [[Roland Emmerich]] would be directing the World War II film ''Midway.''<ref name=\"May2017D\">{{cite news|last1=Fleming Jr|first1=Mike |title=Bona Film Group Stakes $80M On Roland Emmerich/Mark Gordon WWII Battle Pic 'Midway:' Cannes|url=https://deadline.com/2017/05/midway-roland-emmerich-bona-film-group-mark-gordon-1202101145/|accessdate=May 24, 2017|work=Deadline|date=May 23, 2017}}</ref> Due to its potential lofty budget (with estimates putting its needed cost at $125 million), Emmerich had trouble getting the film greenlit. When no major studio would bankroll the project, he cut down on potential battle sequences and turned to individuals for the funds, resulting in $76 million; he then got an additional $24 million in equity, mostly from Chinese investors, resulting in the film's $100 million budget. It is one of the most costly [[independent films]] ever made.<ref name=Budget/> Emmerich has previously attempted to mount the film at [[Sony Pictures]] in the '90s, with [[William Goldman]] becoming interested in the project. However, as with the final rendition, executives balked at the proposed $100 million budget ($152 million by 2019 inflation), and Emmerich moved on to direct ''[[The Patriot (2000 film)|The Patriot]]''.<ref name=\"Variety_Midway\">{{cite news |url=https://variety.com/2019/film/features/roland-emmerich-midway-1203387268/|work=Variety |title=Roland Emmerich Just Made a $100 Million Indie Film. Will It Work? |date=31 October 2019 | author1=Donnelly, Matt}}</ref>\n\nIn April 2018, [[Woody Harrelson]] and [[Mandy Moore]] joined the ensemble cast for the film.<ref name=\"May2018D\">{{cite news|last1=Wiseman|first1=Andreas|title=Roland Emmerich's WWII Epic 'Midway' Sets Sail With Woody Harrelson, Mandy Moore & AGC Studios \u2014 Cannes Hot Pic|url=https://deadline.com/2018/05/roland-emmerichs-wwii-epic-midway-sets-sail-with-woody-harrelson-mandy-moore-agc-studios-1202374631/|accessdate=May 4, 2018|work=Deadline|date=May 2, 2018}}</ref> In July 2018, [[Luke Evans]] was cast in the film to play Lieutenant Commander Wade McClusky, who was awarded the Navy Cross for his role in the Battle of Midway.<ref name=\"EvansCast\">{{cite news |last1=Kit |first1=Borys |title=Luke Evans Joins Roland Emmerich's Naval Action Movie 'Midway' (Exclusive) |url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/heat-vision/luke-evans-joins-roland-emmerichs-naval-movie-midway-1124746 |accessdate=July 6, 2018 |work=The Hollywood Reporter |date=July 3, 2018 |language=en}}</ref> Robby Baumgartner was hired as [[cinematographer]].<ref name=\"Cinematographer\">{{cite news |last1=Marc |first1=Christopher |title=Roland Emmerich's WWII Epic 'Midway' Adds 'The Guest' Cinematographer - GWW |url=https://thegww.com/roland-emmerichs-wwii-epic-midway-adds-the-guest-cinematographer/ |accessdate=July 24, 2018 |work=thegww.com |date=July 24, 2018}}</ref> August saw the additions of [[Patrick Wilson (American actor)|Patrick Wilson]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2018/08/patrick-wilson-midway-roland-emmerich-wwii-film-1202442695/|title=Patrick Wilson Boards Roland Emmerich's 'Midway'|first1=Mike |last1=Fleming Jr|date=August 8, 2018|work=Deadline}}</ref> [[Ed Skrein]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2018/film/news/ed-skrein-roland-emmerichs-midway-1202901290/|title=Ed Skrein Joins Roland Emmerich's World War II Film 'Midway' (EXCLUSIVE)|first1=Justin|last1=Kroll|date=August 9, 2018|work=Variety}}</ref> [[Aaron Eckhart]], [[Nick Jonas]], [[Tadanobu Asano]], [[Dennis Quaid]], and others to the cast.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2018/08/aaron-eckhart-nick-jonas-keean-johnson-tadanobu-asano-midway-roland-emmerich-1202443585/|title=Roland Emmerich's 'Midway' Enlists Aaron Eckhart, Nick Jonas, Tadanobu Asano, Keean Johnson, Ahead Of Fall Shoot|first1=Andreas|last1=Wiseman|date=August 10, 2018|work=Deadline}}</ref> [[Darren Criss]], [[Alexander Ludwig]], and [[Brandon Sklenar]] were cast in September.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2018/09/midway-wwii-film-darren-criss-roland-emmerich-the-assassination-of-gianni-versace-american-crime-story-1202463311/|title=Emmy-Nominated 'Versace' Star Darren Criss Boards Roland Emmerich's 'Midway'|first1=Mike |last1=Fleming Jr|date=September 12, 2018|work=Deadline}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2018/film/news/vikings-star-alexander-ludwig-roland-emmerichs-midway-1202940116/|title='Vikings' Star Alexander Ludwig Joins Roland Emmerich's 'Midway' (EXCLUSIVE)|first1=Justin|last1=Kroll|date=September 13, 2018|work=Variety}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2018/09/brandon-sklenar-roland-emmerich-midway-tanner-beard-we-summon-the-darkness-1202467727/|title=Brandon Sklenar Joins Roland Emmerich's 'Midway'; Tanner Beard Cast In 'We Summon The Darkness'|first1=Amanda|last1=N'Duka|date=September 19, 2018|work=Deadline}}</ref> Filming began on September 5, 2018, in [[Honolulu]], [[Hawaii]]. It was also shot in [[Montreal]], [[Quebec]].<ref name=\"Cinematographer\" />\n\nIn November 2018, it was announced that VFX company [[Scanline VFX]] will be the main VFX vendor, and that [[Pixomondo]] had signed on to provide additional visual effects.\n\n==Release==\n[[File:Jobeth Devera, Dennis Quaid, Woody Harrelson, Jennifer Lahmers and Patrick Wilson .jpg|thumb|right|300px|A photo from a press junket for the film]]\nThe film was released on November 8, 2019, [[Veteran\u2019s Day]] weekend.<ref>{{cite news |last1=D'Alessandro |first1=Anthony |title=Roland Emmerich's WWII Epic 'Midway' To Open Veterans Day Weekend 2019 |url=https://deadline.com/2018/09/roland-emmerichs-wwii-epic-midway-to-open-veterans-day-weekend-2019-1202457811/ |accessdate=September 6, 2018 |work=Deadline |date=September 5, 2018}}</ref>\n\n===Marketing===\nA teaser poster for the film was released on June 4, 2019, which was also the 77th anniversary of the Battle of Midway.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.military.com/off-duty/2019/06/04/take-first-look-falls-wwii-epic-midway.html|title=Take a First Look at This Fall's WWII Epic 'Midway'|first=James|last=Barber|date=June 4, 2019|website=Military.com|accessdate=June 27, 2019}}</ref> A set of 13 still photographs depicting scenes from the film was released on June 26, 2019, and the first trailer for the film was released the following day (June 27).<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/life/movies/2019/06/26/midway-exclusive-first-look-roland-emmerich-all-star-wwii-film/1563788001/|title=Exclusive: Watch the first trailer for 'Midway,' Roland Emmerich's World War II epic|first=Brian|last=Truitt|website=USA TODAY}}</ref> The second and final trailer of the film was released on September 12, 2019, with the film's theatrical poster on September 25.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.comingsoon.net/movies/trailers/1098543-midway-trailer#62Zkw3OCYuBQooy1.99|title=New Midway Trailer: The Courage of a Few Will Change the Fate of the World|first=Kylie|last=Hemmert|work=[[ComingSoon.net]]|date=September 12, 2019|accessdate=October 16, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.vitalthrills.com/2019/09/25/midway-poster-the-roland-emmerich-film/|title=New Midway Poster: The Roland Emmerich Film Opening Nov. 8|first=Mirko|last=Parlevliet|work=Vital Thrills|date=September 25, 2019|accessdate=October 16, 2019}}</ref> All-in-all, Lionsgate spent around $40 million promoting the film.<ref name=opening/>\n\n===Home media===\n''Midway'' was released on [[Digital HD]] on February 4, 2020 and in [[DVD]] and [[Blu-ray]] on February 18, 2020.<ref>{{Cite web | url=https://www.dvdsreleasedates.com/movies/9229/midway/ |title = Midway DVD Release Date February 18, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Reception==\n===Box office===\n''Midway'' grossed $56.8 million in the United States and Canada, and $68.5 million on other territories, for a worldwide total of $125.4 million, against a production budget of $100 million.<ref name=BOM/>\n\nIn the United States and Canada, ''Midway'' was released alongside ''[[Doctor Sleep (2019 film)|Doctor Sleep]]'', ''[[Playing with Fire (2019 film)|Playing with Fire]]'' and ''[[Last Christmas (film)|Last Christmas]]'', and was projected to gross around $15 million from 3,242 theaters in its opening weekend.<ref>{{cite web |url= https://deadline.com/2019/11/doctor-sleep-weekend-box-office-opening-stephen-king-emilia-clarke-last-christmas-terminator-1202779022/ |title= 'Doctor Sleep' Eyes $25M-$30M Box Office Start, Will Turn Out Lights On 'Terminator: Dark Fate' |last=D'Alessandro |first=Anthony |work=[[Deadline Hollywood]] |date=November 6, 2019 |accessdate=November 6, 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"auto\">{{cite web |url= https://variety.com/2019/film/news/box-office-midway-doctor-sleep-last-christmas-1203398724/ |title=Box Office: 'Midway' Could Defeat 'Doctor Sleep' With $21 Million |last=McNary |first=Denis |work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]] |date=November 8, 2019 |accessdate=November 8, 2019}}</ref> The film made $6.3 million on its first day (including $925,000 from Thursday night previews). It went on to debut to $17.5 million, beating box office expectations and upsetting projected winner ''Doctor Sleep'' by finishing first at the box office.<ref name=opening>{{cite web |url= https://deadline.com/2019/11/doctor-sleep-midway-last-christmas-opening-weekend-box-office-1202780077/ |title= How 'Doctor Sleep' Went Into A Coma At The B.O. With Dreary $14M+ Opening, Following Surprise $17M+ Attack By 'Midway' \u2013 Update |last=D'Alessandro |first=Anthony |work=[[Deadline Hollywood]] |date=November 10, 2019 |accessdate=November 10, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite new|url=https://variety.com/2019/film/box-office/midway-doctor-sleep-box-office-surprise-1203399829/|title=\u2018Midway\u2019 Defeats \u2018Doctor Sleep\u2019 in Surprise Box Office Upset|last=Rubin|first=Rebecca|publisher=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|date=November 10, 2019|accessdate=November 27, 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"auto\"/> In its second weekend the film made $8.8 million, finishing second behind newcomer ''[[Ford v Ferrari]]''.<ref>{{cite web |url= https://deadline.com/2019/11/ford-v-ferrari-charlies-angels-weekend-box-office-1202787070/ |title= 'Ford v Ferrari' Cruising To $30M+, 'Charlie's Angels' Kicked Out Of Heaven With $8M+ Start |last=D'Alessandro |first=Anthony |work=[[Deadline Hollywood]] |date=November 17, 2019 |accessdate=November 17, 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Critical response===\nOn [[review aggregator]] [[Rotten Tomatoes]], the film holds an approval rating of 43% based on 157 reviews, with an [[average rating]] of 5.22/10. The website's critics consensus reads, \"''Midway'' revisits a well-known story with modern special effects and a more balanced point of view, but its screenplay isn't quite ready for battle.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/midway_2019|title=Midway (2019)|website=[[Rotten Tomatoes]]|publisher=[[Fandango Media]]|access-date=April 7, 2020}}</ref> On [[Metacritic]], the film has a weighted average score of 47 out of 100, based on 28 critics, indicating \"mixed or average reviews\".<ref>{{cite web|title=Midway (2019) Reviews|url= https://www.metacritic.com/movie/midway|website=[[Metacritic]]|publisher=[[CBS Interactive]]|accessdate=November 12, 2019}}</ref> Audiences polled by [[CinemaScore]] gave the film an average grade of \"A\" on an A+ to F scale, while those at [[PostTrak]] gave it an average 4 out of 5 stars, with 58% saying they would definitely recommend it.<ref name=opening/>\n\n==Historical accuracy==\nThe film does not include Vice Admiral [[Frank Jack Fletcher]], who was the actual tactical commander in both the Battle of the Coral Sea and the Battle of Midway.<ref name=\"Lundstrom\">Lundstrom, John B. (2005). The First Team: Pacific Naval Air Combat from Pearl Harbor to Midway (New ed.). Annapolis, Maryland: Naval Institute Press. {{ISBN|1-59114-471-X}}.</ref> Instead, the film shows Rear Admiral Raymond Spruance as the tactical commander during the Battle of Midway.\n\nThe air battle during the [[Marshalls\u2013Gilberts raids]] is portrayed in the film to take place over a mountainous terrain. However, [[Marshall Islands]] and [[Gilbert Islands]], where the actual raids took place, are [[atoll]]s with very low terrain [[elevation]].\n\nWhile the film shows [[Mitsubishi A6M Zero]] fighters present during the Marshalls\u2013Gilberts raids, [[Imperial Japanese Navy Air Service]] units stationed in the area ([[Chitose Air Group]] and [[Yokohama Air Group]]) did not possess the new Zero type of fighters at the time but operated only the older [[Mitsubishi A5M]] fighters.<ref name=\"Lundstrom\" /> Likewise, there were few Judys on the Japanese carriers; the bombers were more likely to be the [[Aichi D3A|D3A Vals]].\n\nAn inaccuracy was also depicted with the USS [[USS Nautilus (SS-168)|'' Nautilus'']] attacking an enemy carrier but the torpedo missing its target. The destroyer [[Japanese destroyer Arashi|'' Arashi'']] keeps the submarine pinned down so that the carriers can escape; in fact the submarine was actually targeting the [[Japanese battleship Kirishima|Japanese battleship ''Kirishima'']]. \n\nThe film shows some [[Douglas TBD Devastator]] planes carrying both bombs and torpedoes at the same time.  While the Devastator could be equipped with bombs or torpedoes, strike packages were commonly geared to either torpedo attack or level bombing due to the aircraft's low maximum takeoff weight. The TBD-1 Devastator would normally mount a single Mark 13 torpedo in its torpedo bomber configuration, however some of the aircraft are depicted carrying two additional 100 LB GP bombs in sling racks along with the torpedo. These two racks were commonly used for 500 LB GP bombs when the aircraft was not carrying a torpedo. Although nearly all of the 41 TBD-1s present at Midway were armed solely with the Mark 13 torpedo, a select few pilots did attach additional ordinance to their aircraft, however they were the exception and not the norm.<ref name=\"AI Mar90 p152\">{{cite journal |title=Devastator...The Not-so-Devastating TBD-1 |journal=Air International |date=March 1990 |page=152}}</ref><ref>Buell 1987, p. 494.</ref>\n\nThe film depicts the deaths of O'Flaherty and Gaido as happening on the day of the battle just after the loss of the aircraft carriers [[Japanese aircraft carrier Kaga|''Kaga'']]'', [[Japanese aircraft carrier Akagi|''Akagi'']]'' and [[Japanese aircraft carrier S\u014dry\u016b|''S\u014dry\u016b'']], whereas in reality, it happened after two weeks. The film shows Gaido as being thrown overboard with an anchor by the Japanese for refusing to answer questions, but O'Flaherty's death is not shown. In reality, they were interrogated and tortured. After two weeks, they were then killed by being tied to water-filled kerosene cans and thrown overboard to drown.<ref>{{harvnb|Barde|1983|pp=188\u2013192}}</ref><ref name=\"Battle 360\">{{citation|title=Battle 360 - Vengeance at Midway|agency=The History Channel}}</ref>\n\nIn another scene Admiral Yamamoto speaks aloud [[Isoroku Yamamoto's sleeping giant quote|\"We have awakened a sleeping giant and filled him with terrible resolve\"]], a quote which was spoken in the 1970 film ''[[Tora! Tora! Tora!]]'', even though there is no evidence that Yamamoto said this in reality.<ref>{{cite book |last=Safire |first=William |authorlink=William Safire |title=Safire's Political Dictionary |publisher=Oxford University Press |year=2008 |isbn=0195343344 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=c4UoX6-Sv1AC&pg=PA666 |page=666}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Midway (1976 film)|''Midway'' (1976 film)]]\n*''[[Pearl Harbor (film)|Pearl Harbor]]''\n* [[Zhejiang-Jiangxi campaign]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Official website}}\n* {{IMDb title}}\n* {{AllMovie title}}\n\n{{Roland Emmerich}}\n\n[[Category:English-language films]]\n[[Category:Films directed by Roland Emmerich]]\n[[Category:Films scored by Harald Kloser]]\n[[Category:American epic films]]\n[[Category:American films]]\n[[Category:American action drama films]]\n[[Category:American historical films]]\n[[Category:American war drama films]]\n[[Category:Pacific War films]]\n[[Category:2010s action drama films]]\n[[Category:2010s war drama films]]\n[[Category:2010s historical films]]\n[[Category:2010s action war films]]\n[[Category:World War II films based on actual events]]\n[[Category:Battle of Midway]]\n[[Category:Works about Pacific theatre of World War II]]\n[[Category:Action films based on actual events]]\n[[Category:Lions Gate Entertainment films]]\n[[Category:Entertainment One films]]\n[[Category:Summit Entertainment films]]\n[[Category:Films set in the Pacific Ocean]]\n[[Category:Films shot in Honolulu]]\n[[Category:Films shot in Montreal]]\n[[Category:War epic films]]\n[[Category:Cultural depictions of Isoroku Yamamoto]]\n[[Category:American action war films]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|2019 film directed by Roland Emmerich}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = Midway\n| image          = Midway Movie HD Poster.jpeg\n| alt            = \n| caption        = Theatrical release poster\n| director       = [[Roland Emmerich]]\n| producer       = {{Plainlist|\n* Roland Emmerich\n* [[Harald Kloser]]\n}}\n| writer         = Wes Tooke\n| based on       = \n| starring       = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Ed Skrein]]\n* [[Patrick Wilson (American actor)|Patrick Wilson]]\n* [[Luke Evans]]\n* [[Aaron Eckhart]]\n* [[Nick Jonas]]\n* [[Etsushi Toyokawa]]\n* [[Tadanobu Asano]]\n* [[Luke Kleintank]]\n* [[Jun Kunimura]]\n* [[Darren Criss]]\n* [[Keean Johnson]]\n* [[Mandy Moore]]\n* [[Dennis Quaid]]\n* [[Woody Harrelson]]\n}}\n| music          = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Thomas Wander]]\n* Harald Kloser\n}}\n| cinematography = Robby Baumgartner\n| editing        = {{Plainlist|\n* Adam Wolfe\n}}\n| studio       = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Summit Entertainment]]\n* [[Centropolis Entertainment]]\n* [[Entertainment One]]\n* RuYi Media\n* Starlight Culture Entertainment Group\n* Street Entertainment\n* AGC Studios\n}}\n| distributor    = [[Lionsgate]]\n| released       = {{Film date|2019|11|8|United States}}\n| runtime        = 138 minutes\n| country        = United States\n| language       = English\n| budget         = $100 million<ref name=Budget>{{cite news|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/box-office-doctor-sleep-midway-surprise-battle-no-1-1253534|title=Box Office: 'Midway' Downs 'Doctor Sleep' in Surprise Upset |date=November 8, 2019|work=The Hollywood Reporter |author1=Pamela McClintock}}</ref>\n| gross          = $125.8 million<ref name=\"BOM\">{{Cite web |url= https://www.boxofficemojo.com/title/tt6924650 |title=Midway (2019) |website=[[Box Office Mojo]] |accessdate=January 17, 2020}}</ref>\n}}\n\n'''''Midway''''' is a 2019 American  [[Epic film|epic]] [[war film]] directed by [[Roland Emmerich]], who produced the film with [[Harald Kloser]], and written by Wes Tooke. The film features an [[ensemble cast]], including [[Ed Skrein]], [[Patrick Wilson (American actor)|Patrick Wilson]], [[Luke Evans]], [[Aaron Eckhart]], [[Nick Jonas]], [[Mandy Moore]], [[Dennis Quaid]], [[Tadanobu Asano]], and [[Woody Harrelson]].\n\nA passion project of Emmerich's, he had trouble getting financial support for the film before finally fundraising most of the budget and officially announcing it in 2017. Much of the cast joined in summer 2018, and filming began in [[Hawaii]] that September, also taking place in [[Montreal]]. With a production budget of $100 million, it is one of the most expensive [[independent films]] of all time.\n\n''Midway'' was theatrically released by [[Lionsgate]] in the United States on November 8, 2019. It received mixed reviews from critics and grossed $125 million worldwide.\n\n== Plot ==\nThe film follows the story of US Navy sailors and aviators who persevere through the [[Battle of Midway]], a turning point in the [[Pacific Ocean theater of World War II|Pacific Theater]] of [[World War II]]. It follows two threads: one centered on naval aviator Ensign [[Richard Halsey Best|Dick Best]] and the Air Group (CAG) of the carrier [[USS Enterprise (CV-6)|''Enterprise'']], and the other on intelligence officer [[Edwin T. Layton]].\n\nThe film starts with the US Naval attach\u00e9 in [[Tokyo]] and his counterpart discussing the US and Japanese positions in the Pacific Ocean during a state function in December 1937. Admiral [[Isoroku Yamamoto]] warns Layton that if the Japanese oil supply is threatened by the US, the Japanese will take immediate action. The story then goes on briefly to show the [[Attack on Pearl Harbor]] (December 1941), the [[Marshalls-Gilberts raids]] (February 1942), [[Doolittle Raid]] (April 1942), and the [[Battle of the Coral Sea]] (May 1942). It finally describes the planning for the Battle of Midway (June 1942), depicting the creation of a complicated battle plan. [[Joseph Rochefort]] and his cryptology team begin intercepting messages concerning a location the Japanese identify as \"AF\". Layton speaks with Admiral [[Chester Nimitz]], who informs him that Washington believes \"AF\" to be a target in the South Pacific. Layton disagrees, believing the intended target to be [[Midway Atoll]]. \n\nAfter meeting with Rochefort, Nimitz instructs the team to find a way to definitively prove that \"AF\u201d is Midway. After Layton instructs Midway to telegraph in the clear (unencrypted) that they are suffering a water shortage, cryptologists working for Rochefort intercept Japanese communications concerning water shortages on \u201cAF\u201d, confirming that \"AF\" is indeed Midway. In preparation for an ambush of the Japanese fleet, Nimitz orders carriers [[USS Hornet (CV-8)|''Hornet'']] and ''Enterprise'' recalled from the Coral Sea and demands that the damaged [[USS Yorktown (CV-5)|'' Yorktown'']] be made ready for combat operations. \n\nDuring the first stages of the battle, the submarine USS Nautilus manages to slip through the defensive row of Japanese destroyers and fire a torpedo at a carrier. The torpedo misses, and Admiral [[Tamon Yamaguchi]] orders the IJN Arashi to sink the Nautilus while the Japanese carriers make a quick getaway. While Arashi is headed back to the fleet, the US carrier dive bombers led by [[C. Wade McClusky]] follow the destroyer's wake. The gamble pays off and three of the Japanese carriers are destroyed in the first attack during the Battle of Midway. \n\nSpruance then orders what is remaining of the US Air Group to finish off the last carrier. Along their route, they are intercepted by Japanese fighters and bombers on their way to destroy American carriers. A huge [[dogfight]] ensues and many planes from both sides are destroyed. The remaining American planes attack the Hiryu with Lieutenant Best scoring a critical hit with a 500-pound bomb; Hiryu is later scuttled by torpedoes from a Japanese destroyer. Half of the U.S. planes are destroyed in the battle, including most of the [[torpedo bomber]] squadrons.\n\nIn Pearl Harbor, Rochefort intercepts the Japanese order to withdraw and passes it to Layton, who then informs Nimitz and his elated staff. The movie ends with a scene revealing the fates of the principal characters.\n\n==Cast==\n\n=== Allies ===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|- \"\n!Actor\n!Role\n!Notes\n|-\n|[[Ed Skrein]]\n|[[Lieutenant (navy)|Lieutenant]] [[Richard Halsey Best|Richard \"Dick\" Best]]||[[Executive officer]], Bombing Squadron Six, {{USS|Enterprise|CV-6|6}}\n|-\n|[[Patrick Wilson (American actor)|Patrick Wilson]]\n|[[Lieutenant Commander (United States)|Lieutenant Commander]] [[Edwin T. Layton]]||Intelligence officer, [[United States Pacific Fleet|US Pacific Fleet]]\n|-\n|[[Luke Evans]]\n|[[Lieutenant Commander (United States)|Lieutenant Commander]] [[C. Wade McClusky|Wade McClusky]]\n|Air group commander, {{USS|Enterprise|CV-6|6}}\n|-\n|[[Aaron Eckhart]]\n|[[Lieutenant colonel (United States)|Lieutenant Colonel]] [[Jimmy Doolittle]]\n|[[United States Army Air Forces|USAAF]] flight commander, {{USS|Hornet|CV-8|6}}\n|-\n|[[Nick Jonas]]\n|[[Aviation machinist's mate|Aviation Machinist's Mate]] Bruno Gaido\n|Aviation crew, {{USS|Enterprise|CV-6|6}}\n|-\n|[[Woody Harrelson]]\n|[[Admiral (United States)|Admiral]] [[Chester W. Nimitz]]\n|[[Commander-in-chief]], [[United States Pacific Fleet|US Pacific Fleet]]\n|-\n|[[Dennis Quaid]]\n|[[Vice Admiral (United States)|Vice Admiral]] [[William Halsey Jr.|William \"Bull\" Halsey]]\n|Commander, [[Carrier_Strike_Group_2#Historical_background|Carrier Division Two]]\n|-\n|[[Darren Criss]]\n|[[Lieutenant Commander (United States)|Lieutenant Commander]] [[Eugene E. Lindsey|Eugene Lindsey]]\n|Commander, Torpedo Squadron 6, {{USS|Enterprise|CV-6|6}}\n|-\n|[[Jake Weber]]\n|[[Rear Admiral (United States)|Rear Admiral]] [[Raymond Spruance]]\n|Commander, [[Task Force 16]]\n|-\n|[[Brennan Brown]]\n|[[Commander (United States)|Commander]] [[Joseph Rochefort]]\n|[[Cryptanalysis|Chief Cryptanalyst]], [[Station HYPO|Fleet Radio Unit Pacific]]\n|-\n|[[Alexander Ludwig]]\n|[[Lieutenant (navy)|Lieutenant]] Roy Pearce\n|Watch officer, {{USS|Arizona|BB-39|6}}\n|-\n|[[David Hewlett]]\n|[[Admiral (United States)|Admiral]] [[Husband E. Kimmel]]\n|[[Commander-in-chief]], [[United States Pacific Fleet|US Pacific Fleet]]\n|-\n|[[Keean Johnson]]\n|[[Radioman|Chief Aviation Radioman]] James Murray\n|Radio operator, Bombing Squadron Six, {{USS|Enterprise|CV-6|6}}\n|-\n|[[Mark Rolston]]\n|[[Admiral (United States)|Admiral]] [[Ernest King]]\n|[[Chief of Naval Operations]]\n|-\n|[[Luke Kleintank]]\n|[[Lieutenant (navy)|Lieutenant]] Clarence Earle Dickinson\n|Pilot, Scouting Squadron 6, {{USS|Enterprise|CV-6|6}}\n|-\n|[[Brandon Sklenar]]\n|[[Ensign (rank)#United States|Ensign]] [[George H. Gay Jr.|George Gay]]\n|Pilot, [[VT-8|Torpedo Squadron 8]], {{USS|Hornet|CV-8|6}}\n|-\n|[[Jake Manley]]\n|[[Ensign (rank)#United States|Ensign]] Willie West<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.abookof.us/nextchapters/jake-manley|title=Jake Manley: Interview|last=|first=|date=May 18, 2019|work=A Book of Magazine|accessdate=June 3, 2019}}</ref>\n|Pilot, Bombing Squadron 6, {{USS|Enterprise|CV-6|6}}\n|-\n|Eric Davis\n|[[Captain (United States O-6)|Captain]] [[Miles Browning]]\n|Halsey's chief of staff, {{USS|Enterprise|CV-6|6}}\n|-\n|Kenny Leu\n|Zhu Xuesan\n|Chinese school teacher, who visited the US in 1992\n|-\n|[[James Carpinello]]\n|[[Lieutenant Commander (United States)|Lieutenant Commander]] [[William H. Brockman Jr.|William Brockman]]\n|[[Captain]], {{USS|Nautilus|SS-168|6}}\n|-\n|Russell Dennis Lewis\n|[[Ensign (rank)#United States|Ensign]] Frank Woodrow O'Flaherty\n|Pilot, Scouting Squadron 6, {{USS|Enterprise|CV-6|6}}\n|-\n|Jacob Blair\n|[[2nd lieutenant|2nd Lieutenant]] Hank Potter\n|[[United States Army Air Forces|USAAF]] flight navigator, {{USS|Hornet|CV-8|6}}\n|-\n|James Hicks\n|[[Lieutenant (junior grade)|Lieutenant Junior Grade]] Edwin Kroeger\n|Pilot, Bombing Squadron Six, {{USS|Enterprise|CV-6|6}}\n|-\n|[[Geoffrey Blake (actor)|Geoffrey Blake]]\n|Commander [[John Ford]]\n|[[Film director]] stationed at [[Midway Atoll|Midway Island]] on Special Duty\n|}\n\n=== Japanese ===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|- \"\n! style=\"width:125px;\" |Actor\n! style=\"width:200px;\" |Role\n! style=\"width:500px;\" |Notes\n|-\n|[[Tadanobu Asano]]\n|[[Rear Admiral]] [[Tamon Yamaguchi]]\n|Commander, [[Second Carrier Division|2nd Carrier Division]]\n|-\n|[[Etsushi Toyokawa]]\n|[[Admiral#Japan|Admiral]] [[Isoroku Yamamoto]]\n|[[Commander-in-chief]], [[Combined Fleet]]\n|-\n|[[Jun Kunimura]]\n|[[Vice Admiral]] [[Ch\u016bichi Nagumo]]\n|Commander, [[1st Air Fleet]] (''[[Kido Butai]]'')\n|-\n|[[Peter Shinkoda]]\n|[[Captain]] [[Minoru Genda]]\n|Air Operations Officer, [[1st Air Fleet]]\n|-\n|Nobuya Shimamoto\n|[[Captain]] Tomeo Kaku\n|Commanding Officer, [[Japanese aircraft carrier Hiry\u016b|''Hiry\u016b'']]\n|-\n|[[Hiro Kanagawa]]\n|[[Commander]] Isamu Fujita\n|Commanding Officer, [[Japanese destroyer Makigumo (1941)|''Makigumo'']]\n|-\n|Ken Takikawa\n|[[Lieutenant]] Takashi Moroishi\n|Torpedo Officer (XO), [[Japanese destroyer Makigumo (1941)|''Makigumo'']]\n|-\n|Hiromoto Ida\n|[[Army general|General]] [[Hideki Tojo]]\n|[[Prime Minister of Japan]]\n|-\n|Hiroaki Shintani\n|[[Emperor Hirohito]]\n|[[Emperor of Japan]]\n|-\n|Ryuta Kato\n|Japanese Junior Officer (Yamat)\n|Junior Officer, [[Japanese aircraft carrier Hiry\u016b|''Hiry\u016b'']]\n|}\n\n=== Civilians ===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|- \"\n! style=\"width:125px;\" |Actor\n! style=\"width:200px;\" |Role\n! style=\"width:500px;\" |Notes\n|-\n|[[Mandy Moore]]\n|Anne Best\n|Dick Best's wife\n|-\n|Rachael Perrell Fosket\n|Dagne Layton\n|Edwin Layton's wife\n|-\n|Dean Schaller\n|[[Jack MacKenzie]]\n|Ford's [[cameraman]]\n|-\n|Christie Brooke\n|Millicent McClusky\n|Wade McClusky's wife\n|}\n\n== Production ==\nOn May 23, 2017, it was reported that [[Roland Emmerich]] would be directing the World War II film ''Midway.''<ref name=\"May2017D\">{{cite news|last1=Fleming Jr|first1=Mike |title=Bona Film Group Stakes $80M On Roland Emmerich/Mark Gordon WWII Battle Pic 'Midway:' Cannes|url=https://deadline.com/2017/05/midway-roland-emmerich-bona-film-group-mark-gordon-1202101145/|accessdate=May 24, 2017|work=Deadline|date=May 23, 2017}}</ref> Due to its potential lofty budget (with estimates putting its needed cost at $125 million), Emmerich had trouble getting the film greenlit. When no major studio would bankroll the project, he cut down on potential battle sequences and turned to individuals for the funds, resulting in $76 million; he then got an additional $24 million in equity, mostly from Chinese investors, resulting in the film's $100 million budget. It is one of the most costly [[independent films]] ever made.<ref name=Budget/> Emmerich has previously attempted to mount the film at [[Sony Pictures]] in the '90s, with [[William Goldman]] becoming interested in the project. However, as with the final rendition, executives balked at the proposed $100 million budget ($152 million by 2019 inflation), and Emmerich moved on to direct ''[[The Patriot (2000 film)|The Patriot]]''.<ref name=\"Variety_Midway\">{{cite news |url=https://variety.com/2019/film/features/roland-emmerich-midway-1203387268/|work=Variety |title=Roland Emmerich Just Made a $100 Million Indie Film. Will It Work? |date=31 October 2019 | author1=Donnelly, Matt}}</ref>\n\nIn April 2018, [[Woody Harrelson]] and [[Mandy Moore]] joined the ensemble cast for the film.<ref name=\"May2018D\">{{cite news|last1=Wiseman|first1=Andreas|title=Roland Emmerich's WWII Epic 'Midway' Sets Sail With Woody Harrelson, Mandy Moore & AGC Studios \u2014 Cannes Hot Pic|url=https://deadline.com/2018/05/roland-emmerichs-wwii-epic-midway-sets-sail-with-woody-harrelson-mandy-moore-agc-studios-1202374631/|accessdate=May 4, 2018|work=Deadline|date=May 2, 2018}}</ref> In July 2018, [[Luke Evans]] was cast in the film to play Lieutenant Commander Wade McClusky, who was awarded the Navy Cross for his role in the Battle of Midway.<ref name=\"EvansCast\">{{cite news |last1=Kit |first1=Borys |title=Luke Evans Joins Roland Emmerich's Naval Action Movie 'Midway' (Exclusive) |url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/heat-vision/luke-evans-joins-roland-emmerichs-naval-movie-midway-1124746 |accessdate=July 6, 2018 |work=The Hollywood Reporter |date=July 3, 2018 |language=en}}</ref> Robby Baumgartner was hired as [[cinematographer]].<ref name=\"Cinematographer\">{{cite news |last1=Marc |first1=Christopher |title=Roland Emmerich's WWII Epic 'Midway' Adds 'The Guest' Cinematographer - GWW |url=https://thegww.com/roland-emmerichs-wwii-epic-midway-adds-the-guest-cinematographer/ |accessdate=July 24, 2018 |work=thegww.com |date=July 24, 2018}}</ref> August saw the additions of [[Patrick Wilson (American actor)|Patrick Wilson]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2018/08/patrick-wilson-midway-roland-emmerich-wwii-film-1202442695/|title=Patrick Wilson Boards Roland Emmerich's 'Midway'|first1=Mike |last1=Fleming Jr|date=August 8, 2018|work=Deadline}}</ref> [[Ed Skrein]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2018/film/news/ed-skrein-roland-emmerichs-midway-1202901290/|title=Ed Skrein Joins Roland Emmerich's World War II Film 'Midway' (EXCLUSIVE)|first1=Justin|last1=Kroll|date=August 9, 2018|work=Variety}}</ref> [[Aaron Eckhart]], [[Nick Jonas]], [[Tadanobu Asano]], [[Dennis Quaid]], and others to the cast.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2018/08/aaron-eckhart-nick-jonas-keean-johnson-tadanobu-asano-midway-roland-emmerich-1202443585/|title=Roland Emmerich's 'Midway' Enlists Aaron Eckhart, Nick Jonas, Tadanobu Asano, Keean Johnson, Ahead Of Fall Shoot|first1=Andreas|last1=Wiseman|date=August 10, 2018|work=Deadline}}</ref> [[Darren Criss]], [[Alexander Ludwig]], and [[Brandon Sklenar]] were cast in September.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2018/09/midway-wwii-film-darren-criss-roland-emmerich-the-assassination-of-gianni-versace-american-crime-story-1202463311/|title=Emmy-Nominated 'Versace' Star Darren Criss Boards Roland Emmerich's 'Midway'|first1=Mike |last1=Fleming Jr|date=September 12, 2018|work=Deadline}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2018/film/news/vikings-star-alexander-ludwig-roland-emmerichs-midway-1202940116/|title='Vikings' Star Alexander Ludwig Joins Roland Emmerich's 'Midway' (EXCLUSIVE)|first1=Justin|last1=Kroll|date=September 13, 2018|work=Variety}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2018/09/brandon-sklenar-roland-emmerich-midway-tanner-beard-we-summon-the-darkness-1202467727/|title=Brandon Sklenar Joins Roland Emmerich's 'Midway'; Tanner Beard Cast In 'We Summon The Darkness'|first1=Amanda|last1=N'Duka|date=September 19, 2018|work=Deadline}}</ref> Filming began on September 5, 2018, in [[Honolulu]], [[Hawaii]]. It was also shot in [[Montreal]], [[Quebec]].<ref name=\"Cinematographer\" />\n\nIn November 2018, it was announced that VFX company [[Scanline VFX]] will be the main VFX vendor, and that [[Pixomondo]] had signed on to provide additional visual effects.\n\n==Release==\n[[File:Jobeth Devera, Dennis Quaid, Woody Harrelson, Jennifer Lahmers and Patrick Wilson .jpg|thumb|right|300px|A photo from a press junket for the film]]\nThe film was released on November 8, 2019, [[Veteran\u2019s Day]] weekend.<ref>{{cite news |last1=D'Alessandro |first1=Anthony |title=Roland Emmerich's WWII Epic 'Midway' To Open Veterans Day Weekend 2019 |url=https://deadline.com/2018/09/roland-emmerichs-wwii-epic-midway-to-open-veterans-day-weekend-2019-1202457811/ |accessdate=September 6, 2018 |work=Deadline |date=September 5, 2018}}</ref>\n\n===Marketing===\nA teaser poster for the film was released on June 4, 2019, which was also the 77th anniversary of the Battle of Midway.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.military.com/off-duty/2019/06/04/take-first-look-falls-wwii-epic-midway.html|title=Take a First Look at This Fall's WWII Epic 'Midway'|first=James|last=Barber|date=June 4, 2019|website=Military.com|accessdate=June 27, 2019}}</ref> A set of 13 still photographs depicting scenes from the film was released on June 26, 2019, and the first trailer for the film was released the following day (June 27).<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/life/movies/2019/06/26/midway-exclusive-first-look-roland-emmerich-all-star-wwii-film/1563788001/|title=Exclusive: Watch the first trailer for 'Midway,' Roland Emmerich's World War II epic|first=Brian|last=Truitt|website=USA TODAY}}</ref> The second and final trailer of the film was released on September 12, 2019, with the film's theatrical poster on September 25.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.comingsoon.net/movies/trailers/1098543-midway-trailer#62Zkw3OCYuBQooy1.99|title=New Midway Trailer: The Courage of a Few Will Change the Fate of the World|first=Kylie|last=Hemmert|work=[[ComingSoon.net]]|date=September 12, 2019|accessdate=October 16, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.vitalthrills.com/2019/09/25/midway-poster-the-roland-emmerich-film/|title=New Midway Poster: The Roland Emmerich Film Opening Nov. 8|first=Mirko|last=Parlevliet|work=Vital Thrills|date=September 25, 2019|accessdate=October 16, 2019}}</ref> All-in-all, Lionsgate spent around $40 million promoting the film.<ref name=opening/>\n\n===Home media===\n''Midway'' was released on [[Digital HD]] on February 4, 2020 and in [[DVD]] and [[Blu-ray]] on February 18, 2020.<ref>{{Cite web | url=https://www.dvdsreleasedates.com/movies/9229/midway/ |title = Midway DVD Release Date February 18, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Reception==\n===Box office===\n''Midway'' grossed $56.8 million in the United States and Canada, and $68.5 million on other territories, for a worldwide total of $125.4 million, against a production budget of $100 million.<ref name=BOM/>\n\nIn the United States and Canada, ''Midway'' was released alongside ''[[Doctor Sleep (2019 film)|Doctor Sleep]]'', ''[[Playing with Fire (2019 film)|Playing with Fire]]'' and ''[[Last Christmas (film)|Last Christmas]]'', and was projected to gross around $15 million from 3,242 theaters in its opening weekend.<ref>{{cite web |url= https://deadline.com/2019/11/doctor-sleep-weekend-box-office-opening-stephen-king-emilia-clarke-last-christmas-terminator-1202779022/ |title= 'Doctor Sleep' Eyes $25M-$30M Box Office Start, Will Turn Out Lights On 'Terminator: Dark Fate' |last=D'Alessandro |first=Anthony |work=[[Deadline Hollywood]] |date=November 6, 2019 |accessdate=November 6, 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"auto\">{{cite web |url= https://variety.com/2019/film/news/box-office-midway-doctor-sleep-last-christmas-1203398724/ |title=Box Office: 'Midway' Could Defeat 'Doctor Sleep' With $21 Million |last=McNary |first=Denis |work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]] |date=November 8, 2019 |accessdate=November 8, 2019}}</ref> The film made $6.3 million on its first day (including $925,000 from Thursday night previews). It went on to debut to $17.5 million, beating box office expectations and upsetting projected winner ''Doctor Sleep'' by finishing first at the box office.<ref name=opening>{{cite web |url= https://deadline.com/2019/11/doctor-sleep-midway-last-christmas-opening-weekend-box-office-1202780077/ |title= How 'Doctor Sleep' Went Into A Coma At The B.O. With Dreary $14M+ Opening, Following Surprise $17M+ Attack By 'Midway' \u2013 Update |last=D'Alessandro |first=Anthony |work=[[Deadline Hollywood]] |date=November 10, 2019 |accessdate=November 10, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite new|url=https://variety.com/2019/film/box-office/midway-doctor-sleep-box-office-surprise-1203399829/|title=\u2018Midway\u2019 Defeats \u2018Doctor Sleep\u2019 in Surprise Box Office Upset|last=Rubin|first=Rebecca|publisher=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|date=November 10, 2019|accessdate=November 27, 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"auto\"/> In its second weekend the film made $8.8 million, finishing second behind newcomer ''[[Ford v Ferrari]]''.<ref>{{cite web |url= https://deadline.com/2019/11/ford-v-ferrari-charlies-angels-weekend-box-office-1202787070/ |title= 'Ford v Ferrari' Cruising To $30M+, 'Charlie's Angels' Kicked Out Of Heaven With $8M+ Start |last=D'Alessandro |first=Anthony |work=[[Deadline Hollywood]] |date=November 17, 2019 |accessdate=November 17, 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Critical response===\nOn [[review aggregator]] [[Rotten Tomatoes]], the film holds an approval rating of 43% based on 157 reviews, with an [[average rating]] of 5.22/10. The website's critics consensus reads, \"''Midway'' revisits a well-known story with modern special effects and a more balanced point of view, but its screenplay isn't quite ready for battle.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/midway_2019|title=Midway (2019)|website=[[Rotten Tomatoes]]|publisher=[[Fandango Media]]|access-date=April 7, 2020}}</ref> On [[Metacritic]], the film has a weighted average score of 47 out of 100, based on 28 critics, indicating \"mixed or average reviews\".<ref>{{cite web|title=Midway (2019) Reviews|url= https://www.metacritic.com/movie/midway|website=[[Metacritic]]|publisher=[[CBS Interactive]]|accessdate=November 12, 2019}}</ref> Audiences polled by [[CinemaScore]] gave the film an average grade of \"A\" on an A+ to F scale, while those at [[PostTrak]] gave it an average 4 out of 5 stars, with 58% saying they would definitely recommend it.<ref name=opening/>\n\n==Historical accuracy==\nThe film does not include Vice Admiral [[Frank Jack Fletcher]], who was the actual tactical commander in both the Battle of the Coral Sea and the Battle of Midway.<ref name=\"Lundstrom\">Lundstrom, John B. (2005). The First Team: Pacific Naval Air Combat from Pearl Harbor to Midway (New ed.). Annapolis, Maryland: Naval Institute Press. {{ISBN|1-59114-471-X}}.</ref> Instead, the film shows Rear Admiral Raymond Spruance as the tactical commander during the Battle of Midway.\n\nThe air battle during the [[Marshalls\u2013Gilberts raids]] is portrayed in the film to take place over a mountainous terrain. However, [[Marshall Islands]] and [[Gilbert Islands]], where the actual raids took place, are [[atoll]]s with very low terrain [[elevation]].\n\nWhile the film shows [[Mitsubishi A6M Zero]] fighters present during the Marshalls\u2013Gilberts raids, [[Imperial Japanese Navy Air Service]] units stationed in the area ([[Chitose Air Group]] and [[Yokohama Air Group]]) did not possess the new Zero type of fighters at the time but operated only the older [[Mitsubishi A5M]] fighters.<ref name=\"Lundstrom\" />\n\nAn inaccuracy was also depicted with the USS [[USS Nautilus (SS-168)|'' Nautilus'']] attacking an enemy carrier but the torpedo missing its target. The destroyer [[Japanese destroyer Arashi|'' Arashi'']] keeps the submarine pinned down so that the carriers can escape; in fact the submarine was actually targeting the [[Japanese battleship Kirishima|Japanese battleship ''Kirishima'']]. \n\nThe film shows some [[Douglas TBD Devastator]] planes carrying both bombs and torpedoes at the same time.  While the Devastator could be equipped with bombs or torpedoes, strike packages were commonly geared to either torpedo attack or level bombing due to the aircraft's low maximum takeoff weight. The TBD-1 Devastator would normally mount a single Mark 13 torpedo in its torpedo bomber configuration, however some of the aircraft are depicted carrying two additional 100 LB GP bombs in sling racks along with the torpedo. These two racks were commonly used for 500 LB GP bombs when the aircraft was not carrying a torpedo. Although nearly all of the 41 TBD-1s present at Midway were armed solely with the Mark 13 torpedo, a select few pilots did attach additional ordinance to their aircraft, however they were the exception and not the norm.<ref name=\"AI Mar90 p152\">{{cite journal |title=Devastator...The Not-so-Devastating TBD-1 |journal=Air International |date=March 1990 |page=152}}</ref><ref>Buell 1987, p. 494.</ref>\n\nThe film depicts the deaths of O'Flaherty and Gaido as happening on the day of the battle just after the loss of the aircraft carriers [[Japanese aircraft carrier Kaga|''Kaga'']]'', [[Japanese aircraft carrier Akagi|''Akagi'']]'' and [[Japanese aircraft carrier S\u014dry\u016b|''S\u014dry\u016b'']], whereas in reality, it happened after two weeks. The film shows Gaido as being thrown overboard with an anchor by the Japanese for refusing to answer questions, but O'Flaherty's death is not shown. In reality, they were interrogated and tortured. After two weeks, they were then killed by being tied to water-filled kerosene cans and thrown overboard to drown.<ref>{{harvnb|Barde|1983|pp=188\u2013192}}</ref><ref name=\"Battle 360\">{{citation|title=Battle 360 - Vengeance at Midway|agency=The History Channel}}</ref>\n\nIn another scene Admiral Yamamoto speaks aloud [[Isoroku Yamamoto's sleeping giant quote|\"We have awakened a sleeping giant and filled him with terrible resolve\"]], a quote which was spoken in the 1970 film ''[[Tora! Tora! Tora!]]'', even though there is no evidence that Yamamoto said this in reality.<ref>{{cite book |last=Safire |first=William |authorlink=William Safire |title=Safire's Political Dictionary |publisher=Oxford University Press |year=2008 |isbn=0195343344 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=c4UoX6-Sv1AC&pg=PA666 |page=666}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Midway (1976 film)|''Midway'' (1976 film)]]\n*''[[Pearl Harbor (film)|Pearl Harbor]]''\n* [[Zhejiang-Jiangxi campaign]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Official website}}\n* {{IMDb title}}\n* {{AllMovie title}}\n\n{{Roland Emmerich}}\n\n[[Category:English-language films]]\n[[Category:Films directed by Roland Emmerich]]\n[[Category:Films scored by Harald Kloser]]\n[[Category:American epic films]]\n[[Category:American films]]\n[[Category:American action drama films]]\n[[Category:American historical films]]\n[[Category:American war drama films]]\n[[Category:Pacific War films]]\n[[Category:2010s action drama films]]\n[[Category:2010s war drama films]]\n[[Category:2010s historical films]]\n[[Category:2010s action war films]]\n[[Category:World War II films based on actual events]]\n[[Category:Battle of Midway]]\n[[Category:Works about Pacific theatre of World War II]]\n[[Category:Action films based on actual events]]\n[[Category:Lions Gate Entertainment films]]\n[[Category:Entertainment One films]]\n[[Category:Summit Entertainment films]]\n[[Category:Films set in the Pacific Ocean]]\n[[Category:Films shot in Honolulu]]\n[[Category:Films shot in Montreal]]\n[[Category:War epic films]]\n[[Category:Cultural depictions of Isoroku Yamamoto]]\n[[Category:American action war films]]\n", "name_user": "112.211.0.42", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Midway_(2019_film)"}
